00:00:57.086 --> 00:01:00.976 A:middle
&gt;&gt; GoldieBlox just scored a
free 30-second Super Bowl ad.

00:01:02.016 --> 00:01:04.936 A:middle
&gt;&gt; A [inaudible] Thanksgiving
Day float, are you kidding me?

00:01:15.046 --> 00:01:16.926 A:middle
&gt;&gt; The toy of the decade,
there's no doubt about it.

00:01:33.396 --> 00:01:33.926 A:middle
&gt;&gt; GoldieBlox!

00:01:48.516 --> 00:01:56.436 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:01:56.936 --> 00:01:57.836 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Hi, everybody.

00:01:58.006 --> 00:02:00.426 A:middle
I'm Debbie Sterling,
and I'm on a mission


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:01:58.006 --> 00:02:00.426 A:middle
I'm Debbie Sterling,
and I'm on a mission

00:02:01.066 --> 00:02:03.526 A:middle
to get more girls
into engineering.

00:02:04.436 --> 00:02:04.556 A:middle
Yeah!

00:02:05.516 --> 00:02:10.026 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:02:10.526 --> 00:02:12.116 A:middle
&gt;&gt; So it probably
sounds kind of corny,

00:02:12.116 --> 00:02:15.786 A:middle
but this mission is really
what gets me up every morning.

00:02:16.176 --> 00:02:17.256 A:middle
It's what makes me tick.

00:02:17.976 --> 00:02:20.386 A:middle
This mission has led
me to accomplish things

00:02:20.386 --> 00:02:23.906 A:middle
that I never thought were
possible before, like standing

00:02:23.906 --> 00:02:26.106 A:middle
up here right now onstage

00:02:26.106 --> 00:02:29.166 A:middle
at the most important developers
conference in the world.

00:02:29.786 --> 00:02:32.436 A:middle
Can you believe it?

00:02:33.516 --> 00:02:35.546 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:02:36.046 --> 00:02:40.486 A:middle
And this moment, this is just
one of many crazy, outrageous,

00:02:40.596 --> 00:02:43.156 A:middle
audacious goals that
I've set for myself,

00:02:43.476 --> 00:02:44.776 A:middle
all in the name of this mission.

00:02:45.596 --> 00:02:48.966 A:middle
So I'm going to share
my story with you today,

00:02:48.966 --> 00:02:52.306 A:middle
and this is really a
story of audacious goals.

00:02:52.856 --> 00:02:55.546 A:middle
When you dare to be
audacious, amazing,

00:02:55.626 --> 00:02:59.376 A:middle
unbelievable things happen,
like a Super Bowl victory,

00:02:59.656 --> 00:03:01.676 A:middle
a legal battle with
the Beastie Boys,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:02:59.656 --> 00:03:01.676 A:middle
a legal battle with
the Beastie Boys,

00:03:02.276 --> 00:03:05.546 A:middle
and a trip to the tattoo
parlor, just to name a few.

00:03:06.336 --> 00:03:09.826 A:middle
This GoldieBlox has
been a really wild ride,

00:03:10.296 --> 00:03:11.516 A:middle
and I've had a lot

00:03:11.516 --> 00:03:13.206 A:middle
of hard-earned lessons
along the way.

00:03:13.646 --> 00:03:15.906 A:middle
But I hope that this story
today that I'm sharing

00:03:15.906 --> 00:03:19.086 A:middle
with you will inspire all
of you to be audacious

00:03:19.246 --> 00:03:20.726 A:middle
for the things that
you believe in.

00:03:21.056 --> 00:03:25.036 A:middle
So I'm going to start my
story right at the beginning.

00:03:25.666 --> 00:03:27.256 A:middle
This is me when I
was a little girl.

00:03:28.126 --> 00:03:30.886 A:middle
Come on, you can
say it -- awwwwwww.

00:03:31.376 --> 00:03:35.846 A:middle
So I grew up in a small
town, went to public school,

00:03:36.576 --> 00:03:39.406 A:middle
small-town U.S.A., Lincoln,
Rhode Island, to be exact.

00:03:39.766 --> 00:03:41.136 A:middle
Any Rhode Islanders in here?

00:03:41.426 --> 00:03:42.986 A:middle
Oh, there's like one, yes.

00:03:43.876 --> 00:03:48.086 A:middle
So growing up in
Lincoln, Rhode Island,

00:03:48.406 --> 00:03:52.416 A:middle
I remember when I had
my first big break,

00:03:53.026 --> 00:03:56.576 A:middle
and this was I got accepted
into Stanford University.

00:03:57.316 --> 00:03:59.776 A:middle
And this was a really
huge deal for me.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:04:00.076 --> 00:04:02.506 A:middle
No one from my high school
had ever gotten into Stanford.

00:04:02.886 --> 00:04:05.756 A:middle
They announced it on the
loudspeaker, and everyone

00:04:05.756 --> 00:04:06.856 A:middle
in the cafeteria clapped.

00:04:07.656 --> 00:04:11.406 A:middle
It was a huge deal, and
that day my math teacher,

00:04:11.406 --> 00:04:15.236 A:middle
she was my favorite teacher,
pulled me aside and she said,

00:04:15.236 --> 00:04:18.116 A:middle
Debbie, what do you plan
on majoring in at Stanford?

00:04:18.685 --> 00:04:19.616 A:middle
And I said I didn't know.

00:04:20.476 --> 00:04:22.036 A:middle
She said, how about engineering?

00:04:22.466 --> 00:04:23.996 A:middle
I think you would
love engineering.

00:04:24.796 --> 00:04:27.406 A:middle
And I swear to God at that
moment I looked at her

00:04:27.946 --> 00:04:29.976 A:middle
and I pictured an
old man train driver.

00:04:30.441 --> 00:04:32.441 A:middle
[Laughter]

00:04:32.866 --> 00:04:35.906 A:middle
And I really, you know, it's
so funny and it's embarrassing

00:04:35.906 --> 00:04:38.506 A:middle
to admit it, but I really had
no idea what engineering was

00:04:39.216 --> 00:04:41.576 A:middle
and I was too ashamed
of asking her.

00:04:41.856 --> 00:04:45.556 A:middle
So I just kind of shrugged my
shoulders and smiled and said,

00:04:45.556 --> 00:04:47.936 A:middle
sure, Mrs. Verlay,
engineering sounds cool.

00:04:48.496 --> 00:04:51.386 A:middle
So I went off to
Stanford, my freshman year,

00:04:51.666 --> 00:04:54.906 A:middle
and like most typical college
freshman I had no idea what I

00:04:54.906 --> 00:04:55.736 A:middle
wanted to major in.

00:04:55.736 --> 00:04:58.026 A:middle
And her voice stuck in my head,

00:04:58.166 --> 00:04:59.936 A:middle
that you would excel
in engineering.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:05:00.496 --> 00:05:03.626 A:middle
So I signed up for
Mechanical Engineering 101,

00:05:04.126 --> 00:05:07.396 A:middle
and to my surprise I really
fell in love with that class.

00:05:08.086 --> 00:05:11.376 A:middle
And so for the first time
in my life I set myself

00:05:11.446 --> 00:05:15.826 A:middle
out with an audacious
goal: be an engineer.

00:05:17.016 --> 00:05:19.736 A:middle
Now most of you in this
room are probably engineers

00:05:19.786 --> 00:05:22.646 A:middle
so this probably doesn't sound
audacious to you whatsoever,

00:05:23.136 --> 00:05:26.796 A:middle
but for me this was
an unexpected path.

00:05:28.376 --> 00:05:32.246 A:middle
Once I got to Stanford, it was
really only a handful of women

00:05:32.246 --> 00:05:36.116 A:middle
in my classes, and only
14 percent of women

00:05:36.116 --> 00:05:39.526 A:middle
in the U.S. are engineers,
so it's a huge problem.

00:05:40.016 --> 00:05:40.646 A:middle
And I felt that.

00:05:41.486 --> 00:05:45.246 A:middle
Being one of the only girls
in my classes, it would tend

00:05:45.246 --> 00:05:47.236 A:middle
to mean that the
professors, when they split us

00:05:47.236 --> 00:05:50.596 A:middle
up into group projects, I'd
be the only girl in the group.

00:05:51.276 --> 00:05:53.476 A:middle
And I could see the
look on the guys' faces

00:05:53.476 --> 00:05:55.046 A:middle
when they got stuck
with the girl.

00:05:55.906 --> 00:05:58.866 A:middle
And in our group
projects, I always felt

00:05:58.866 --> 00:06:00.426 A:middle
like my ideas were ignored.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:05:58.866 --> 00:06:00.426 A:middle
like my ideas were ignored.

00:06:01.096 --> 00:06:04.866 A:middle
I felt like I'd compare myself
to the guys in my classes

00:06:04.896 --> 00:06:07.096 A:middle
and they just seemed so
much smarter than me,

00:06:07.476 --> 00:06:09.876 A:middle
like they'd been
programming calculators

00:06:09.876 --> 00:06:11.116 A:middle
since they were three.

00:06:11.576 --> 00:06:14.556 A:middle
Many of you in here
probably did do that.

00:06:16.076 --> 00:06:19.046 A:middle
And I really, I never felt
good enough or that I belonged.

00:06:19.516 --> 00:06:23.516 A:middle
I remember the one day that
I almost gave it up entirely.

00:06:24.146 --> 00:06:28.016 A:middle
I had signed up to take an
engineering drawing class.

00:06:28.016 --> 00:06:29.986 A:middle
It was a class where you
had to try and draw things

00:06:29.986 --> 00:06:31.806 A:middle
in 3D, in perspective.

00:06:32.326 --> 00:06:34.096 A:middle
And this class I
was actually excited

00:06:34.096 --> 00:06:36.906 A:middle
about because I'd always
loved art and I figured,

00:06:36.906 --> 00:06:40.336 A:middle
I'm totally going to ace this,
but when I started getting

00:06:40.336 --> 00:06:43.086 A:middle
into the coursework I
struggled with the material.

00:06:43.556 --> 00:06:47.266 A:middle
For some reason, for the life
of me I couldn't draw in 3D.

00:06:47.886 --> 00:06:50.986 A:middle
I tried really hard, and
I remember our final day

00:06:50.986 --> 00:06:53.366 A:middle
of class we had to put
all of our drawings

00:06:53.366 --> 00:06:54.856 A:middle
up on the wall for critique.

00:06:55.616 --> 00:06:58.886 A:middle
And the TAs went around and
they got up to my drawing

00:06:59.596 --> 00:07:02.096 A:middle
and they looked out to the
room, the entire class,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:06:59.596 --> 00:07:02.096 A:middle
and they looked out to the
room, the entire class,

00:07:02.356 --> 00:07:05.346 A:middle
almost all guys, and they
said, raise your hand

00:07:05.346 --> 00:07:07.146 A:middle
if you think Debbie
should pass this class.

00:07:09.976 --> 00:07:13.526 A:middle
And everyone just kind of
stood there, so awkward,

00:07:13.646 --> 00:07:14.876 A:middle
not knowing what to do.

00:07:15.456 --> 00:07:18.956 A:middle
And the teachers asked
again, and I turned beet red.

00:07:19.116 --> 00:07:20.936 A:middle
Everyone is kind of
shuffling their feet,

00:07:20.936 --> 00:07:22.086 A:middle
not knowing what to say.

00:07:22.546 --> 00:07:26.626 A:middle
And, finally, my friend, Micah
got up and he stood up for me,

00:07:27.216 --> 00:07:31.436 A:middle
and he told those TAs that
they were humiliating me

00:07:31.496 --> 00:07:32.626 A:middle
and it was unnecessary.

00:07:33.066 --> 00:07:35.626 A:middle
That it was their job to teach
me, not to make fun of me.

00:07:36.516 --> 00:07:40.386 A:middle
Well, I ran out of that room
and I burst out into tears,

00:07:40.756 --> 00:07:42.036 A:middle
and I'm not much of a crier.

00:07:42.116 --> 00:07:45.696 A:middle
And at that moment I knew
what they were trying to do.

00:07:45.696 --> 00:07:48.416 A:middle
I knew they were trying to
weed me out of the major.

00:07:48.956 --> 00:07:51.176 A:middle
And the worst part was I
felt like I deserved it.

00:07:51.916 --> 00:07:55.626 A:middle
But luckily Micah came to
my side and he told me not

00:07:55.626 --> 00:07:57.596 A:middle
to give up, he told
me to stick with it.

00:07:57.596 --> 00:08:00.026 A:middle
He actually became
an Apple employee,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:07:57.596 --> 00:08:00.026 A:middle
He actually became
an Apple employee,

00:08:01.056 --> 00:08:02.876 A:middle
so he's a pretty
smart guy, right?

00:08:03.516 --> 00:08:05.916 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:08:06.416 --> 00:08:09.316 A:middle
And so I followed his advice
and I did work harder,

00:08:09.316 --> 00:08:10.986 A:middle
harder than I'd ever
worked in my life,

00:08:11.676 --> 00:08:14.086 A:middle
and I earned my engineering
degree.

00:08:15.096 --> 00:08:16.836 A:middle
And on the day that
I graduated ...

00:08:17.336 --> 00:08:21.556 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:08:22.056 --> 00:08:23.996 A:middle
... it was really the
proudest day of my life

00:08:24.336 --> 00:08:27.046 A:middle
because I had set an
audacious goal for myself

00:08:27.336 --> 00:08:29.046 A:middle
and I had achieved it.

00:08:29.046 --> 00:08:30.966 A:middle
And what made it so
much more meaningful is

00:08:30.966 --> 00:08:34.836 A:middle
that it wasn't easy for me, and
once I hit it, once I climbed

00:08:34.836 --> 00:08:36.486 A:middle
that mountain and I achieved it,

00:08:36.756 --> 00:08:38.395 A:middle
I learned something
about myself.

00:08:38.645 --> 00:08:41.196 A:middle
I learned that I really
was capable all along.

00:08:42.366 --> 00:08:45.256 A:middle
On the day of my graduation,
it was the same day

00:08:45.256 --> 00:08:48.836 A:middle
that Steve Jobs gave his
infamous 2005 commencement

00:08:48.946 --> 00:08:52.016 A:middle
speech, and that speech
really changed my life.

00:08:52.726 --> 00:08:56.836 A:middle
He told us all to never settle,
to keep pushing, to keep going

00:08:56.836 --> 00:08:58.636 A:middle
until you find your
true passion,

00:08:59.166 --> 00:09:00.686 A:middle
until you can follow your heart.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:08:59.166 --> 00:09:00.686 A:middle
until you can follow your heart.

00:09:01.516 --> 00:09:04.746 A:middle
And I sat there on
that day deciding:

00:09:04.816 --> 00:09:06.996 A:middle
I'm going to find my passion
and I'm going to follow it,

00:09:06.996 --> 00:09:09.356 A:middle
I just don't really
know what it is.

00:09:09.996 --> 00:09:12.796 A:middle
So I started going out
there trying to find it.

00:09:12.796 --> 00:09:14.916 A:middle
I had a bunch of different jobs.

00:09:15.216 --> 00:09:16.696 A:middle
I traveled the world.

00:09:16.696 --> 00:09:18.406 A:middle
I did volunteer work in India.

00:09:18.406 --> 00:09:21.546 A:middle
I was searching and searching,
I've got to follow my heart,

00:09:21.546 --> 00:09:24.946 A:middle
I just, again, don't
know what that is.

00:09:25.086 --> 00:09:27.626 A:middle
Until finally one day it hit me.

00:09:28.146 --> 00:09:34.806 A:middle
I've got to get more
girls into engineering.

00:09:35.256 --> 00:09:40.946 A:middle
The lack of women in engineering
is a joke, literally.

00:09:41.496 --> 00:09:43.556 A:middle
There are memes about it
all over the Internet,

00:09:43.556 --> 00:09:48.116 A:middle
and everyone here knows, and I
know, that there are millions

00:09:48.116 --> 00:09:50.386 A:middle
of girls out there in the
world who are just like me,

00:09:50.386 --> 00:09:53.106 A:middle
who have it in them but
probably won't get lucky enough

00:09:53.106 --> 00:09:56.176 A:middle
to have a math teacher pull them
aside and encourage them, right?

00:09:56.916 --> 00:10:01.376 A:middle
So I started becoming obsessed
with why there are so few girls


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:09:56.916 --> 00:10:01.376 A:middle
So I started becoming obsessed
with why there are so few girls

00:10:01.516 --> 00:10:04.626 A:middle
and women in engineering and
what I could do to change that.

00:10:05.226 --> 00:10:07.896 A:middle
I started talking about
it with everyone I could,

00:10:07.896 --> 00:10:10.356 A:middle
and asking them, how did
you get into engineering,

00:10:10.356 --> 00:10:12.526 A:middle
and why are there so
few women and girls?

00:10:13.006 --> 00:10:17.356 A:middle
And I started to hear the same
response over and over again:

00:10:17.356 --> 00:10:18.386 A:middle
you can't fight nature.

00:10:19.636 --> 00:10:22.926 A:middle
Seriously, smart, educated
people would tell me, you know,

00:10:23.436 --> 00:10:25.346 A:middle
there are just biological
differences

00:10:25.346 --> 00:10:26.456 A:middle
between men and women.

00:10:26.456 --> 00:10:29.056 A:middle
And they told me, you know,

00:10:29.056 --> 00:10:32.906 A:middle
men just are naturally inclined
toward building and engineering,

00:10:32.906 --> 00:10:34.586 A:middle
they're just good
at it, you know?

00:10:35.066 --> 00:10:38.766 A:middle
They've got spatial skills,
they're born to be engineers.

00:10:39.536 --> 00:10:40.946 A:middle
Well, this really pissed me off.

00:10:43.516 --> 00:10:48.226 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:10:48.726 --> 00:10:50.556 A:middle
It did, I mean I got
into engineering,

00:10:50.556 --> 00:10:52.906 A:middle
does that make me a freak
of nature or something?

00:10:53.756 --> 00:10:57.616 A:middle
So this pissed me off
so much I decided to set

00:10:57.696 --> 00:11:02.136 A:middle
out with my next audacious
goal: I'm going to fight nature.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:10:57.696 --> 00:11:02.136 A:middle
out with my next audacious
goal: I'm going to fight nature.

00:11:02.676 --> 00:11:04.936 A:middle
You say you can't fight nature,
well, I'm going to fight nature.

00:11:05.656 --> 00:11:09.606 A:middle
And what I started to do was
I wanted to get smart on it.

00:11:10.086 --> 00:11:12.326 A:middle
Is there any validity to
what these people are saying?

00:11:12.386 --> 00:11:13.526 A:middle
I'm going to do my homework.

00:11:14.106 --> 00:11:17.626 A:middle
So I started doing research
and read every study I could

00:11:17.666 --> 00:11:18.756 A:middle
on gender differences.

00:11:18.756 --> 00:11:21.516 A:middle
I wanted to know the
difference between the sexes,

00:11:22.686 --> 00:11:26.196 A:middle
those biological drivers
between men and women.

00:11:26.386 --> 00:11:28.066 A:middle
So I read research articles.

00:11:28.066 --> 00:11:29.646 A:middle
I talked to neuroscientists.

00:11:30.076 --> 00:11:32.756 A:middle
I studied cognitive
development in children.

00:11:32.756 --> 00:11:35.376 A:middle
I met with engineers,
and parents,

00:11:35.376 --> 00:11:36.956 A:middle
and teachers, everybody I could.

00:11:37.746 --> 00:11:39.746 A:middle
And I learned some
really interesting things.

00:11:40.626 --> 00:11:43.196 A:middle
First, I learned that,
yes, there are differences

00:11:43.226 --> 00:11:44.366 A:middle
between men and women.

00:11:44.666 --> 00:11:46.616 A:middle
There are differences
between boys and girls.

00:11:47.166 --> 00:11:50.066 A:middle
For example, I learned if
you give a boy a stick,

00:11:50.066 --> 00:11:53.586 A:middle
he will most likely turn it
into a gun and shoot it at you.

00:11:54.636 --> 00:11:55.516 A:middle
This is true, actually,

00:11:55.516 --> 00:11:57.706 A:middle
my three-year-old
cousin literally did this

00:11:57.836 --> 00:11:59.506 A:middle
to me the other day
with my own toys.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:12:00.826 --> 00:12:04.196 A:middle
I also learned that girls
are naturally inclined toward

00:12:04.196 --> 00:12:06.706 A:middle
nurturing, in case they
become a mother someday.

00:12:06.836 --> 00:12:09.826 A:middle
This is why baby dolls
and soft cuddly pets are

00:12:09.826 --> 00:12:11.146 A:middle
so popular with girls.

00:12:12.236 --> 00:12:14.846 A:middle
I learned that in
preschool classrooms,

00:12:15.166 --> 00:12:17.916 A:middle
boys like to compete
mano a mano,

00:12:17.916 --> 00:12:20.066 A:middle
man against man,
winner takes all.

00:12:20.516 --> 00:12:22.176 A:middle
Whereas girls like situations

00:12:22.176 --> 00:12:24.996 A:middle
where everybody works
together toward a common goal,

00:12:25.026 --> 00:12:26.136 A:middle
where everybody wins.

00:12:26.576 --> 00:12:29.926 A:middle
And the way that girls tend to
compete is by excluding others.

00:12:30.326 --> 00:12:32.156 A:middle
It's called cliques,
and I have been

00:12:32.156 --> 00:12:33.726 A:middle
in a few cliques in my life.

00:12:34.996 --> 00:12:37.116 A:middle
And I learned so many
things, but I'll jump ahead

00:12:37.216 --> 00:12:40.806 A:middle
to really I think the
most important study.

00:12:40.986 --> 00:12:41.976 A:middle
It was done recently.

00:12:41.976 --> 00:12:43.586 A:middle
There was a global test.

00:12:44.026 --> 00:12:45.956 A:middle
Around the world they
tested boys and girls

00:12:45.956 --> 00:12:47.456 A:middle
on the same exact science test.

00:12:48.116 --> 00:12:49.406 A:middle
And what the results showed was

00:12:49.406 --> 00:12:53.066 A:middle
that girls actually outperformed
the boys on that test

00:12:53.066 --> 00:12:54.386 A:middle
in most parts of the world,

00:12:54.696 --> 00:12:59.056 A:middle
but not in the U.S. What this
study showed, and many others

00:12:59.056 --> 00:13:00.466 A:middle
that have been done
just like it,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:12:59.056 --> 00:13:00.466 A:middle
that have been done
just like it,

00:13:00.616 --> 00:13:03.396 A:middle
is that there's actually no
innate intellectual difference

00:13:03.446 --> 00:13:06.456 A:middle
between boys and girls in
the math and science fields.

00:13:07.016 --> 00:13:10.386 A:middle
What the study suggests is
that the problem isn't nature,

00:13:11.246 --> 00:13:13.536 A:middle
the problem is actually culture.

00:13:14.426 --> 00:13:17.726 A:middle
And from a young age, girls
and boys when they look

00:13:17.726 --> 00:13:20.816 A:middle
at the world they see
engineering as a boys' club.

00:13:21.316 --> 00:13:26.366 A:middle
You've got Handy Manny; Bob the
Builder; Sid the Science Kid;

00:13:26.566 --> 00:13:32.786 A:middle
Jimmy Neutron, Boy Genius;
Bill Nye, the Science Guy.

00:13:32.786 --> 00:13:35.226 A:middle
From a young age this
is what kids believe,

00:13:35.796 --> 00:13:37.696 A:middle
these are the builders, right?

00:13:38.256 --> 00:13:41.936 A:middle
And what's even worse is
when you look at the world

00:13:42.006 --> 00:13:45.686 A:middle
through the eyes of a kid
it's very clear that dolls are

00:13:45.686 --> 00:13:48.046 A:middle
for girls and building
is for boys.

00:13:49.036 --> 00:13:52.416 A:middle
Take a walk down the pink
aisle and there's princesses,

00:13:52.546 --> 00:14:00.056 A:middle
Barbie Dolls, fashion, literally
ironing boards today in 2015.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:13:52.546 --> 00:14:00.056 A:middle
Barbie Dolls, fashion, literally
ironing boards today in 2015.

00:14:00.356 --> 00:14:04.096 A:middle
It's like we're back in the
1950s, and all the products

00:14:04.096 --> 00:14:07.226 A:middle
and characters for girls
tell girls that beauty

00:14:07.226 --> 00:14:09.226 A:middle
above all is what's important.

00:14:10.186 --> 00:14:11.596 A:middle
Meanwhile, the blue aisle

00:14:11.596 --> 00:14:15.856 A:middle
for boys has the awesome super
heroes and action figures

00:14:15.856 --> 00:14:18.766 A:middle
and brainteasers and
construction sets.

00:14:18.916 --> 00:14:21.886 A:middle
Those things really help
develop an interest in science

00:14:21.886 --> 00:14:23.716 A:middle
and technology, engineering
and math,

00:14:23.716 --> 00:14:25.696 A:middle
develop spatial skills,
tinkering.

00:14:26.336 --> 00:14:30.976 A:middle
So I was in this very pink
aisle four years ago and I felt

00:14:30.976 --> 00:14:32.646 A:middle
like I was in the Twilight Zone.

00:14:33.586 --> 00:14:35.986 A:middle
And at that instant
I just knew in my gut

00:14:36.536 --> 00:14:38.796 A:middle
that this was my
opportunity to change it.

00:14:38.796 --> 00:14:41.556 A:middle
So I came up with an obsession.

00:14:42.456 --> 00:14:45.666 A:middle
I'm going to invent an
engineering toy for girls.

00:14:47.276 --> 00:14:50.096 A:middle
I left the store that
day, filled up a cart

00:14:50.096 --> 00:14:52.826 A:middle
with as many toys as I could
and I decided, all right,

00:14:52.826 --> 00:14:54.096 A:middle
I'm going to start
doing research,

00:14:54.096 --> 00:14:55.086 A:middle
get to the bottom of this.

00:14:55.186 --> 00:14:57.666 A:middle
How can I get girls into
building and construction?

00:14:58.316 --> 00:15:00.786 A:middle
I went around, begged my
friends, please, please,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:14:58.316 --> 00:15:00.786 A:middle
I went around, begged my
friends, please, please,

00:15:00.786 --> 00:15:03.196 A:middle
please let me babysit your kids.

00:15:03.556 --> 00:15:04.856 A:middle
They were like, all right.

00:15:05.526 --> 00:15:08.296 A:middle
But I needed even more
kids, people I didn't know.

00:15:08.296 --> 00:15:12.036 A:middle
I was searching and searching,
how do I find kids to test on?

00:15:12.206 --> 00:15:16.656 A:middle
I even posted -- I posted
an ad on Craigslist.

00:15:17.636 --> 00:15:22.636 A:middle
I did. It said free childcare
for girls four to nine.

00:15:25.276 --> 00:15:28.806 A:middle
And I didn't realize it
sounded so creepy, right?

00:15:30.056 --> 00:15:31.856 A:middle
My husband was like, thank
God you're not trying

00:15:31.856 --> 00:15:34.126 A:middle
to start a babysitting
company, what's wrong with you?

00:15:34.766 --> 00:15:37.916 A:middle
And only one person
replied, this French woman,

00:15:37.916 --> 00:15:40.586 A:middle
who I think it got lost in
translation or something.

00:15:40.586 --> 00:15:42.016 A:middle
She must have been
like, America,

00:15:42.016 --> 00:15:43.576 A:middle
the greatest place in the world!

00:15:44.076 --> 00:15:46.976 A:middle
But I actually went to her house
and I babysat her daughter.

00:15:47.396 --> 00:15:51.376 A:middle
And through all of this time
I spent with kids I started

00:15:51.376 --> 00:15:52.596 A:middle
to notice some patterns.

00:15:53.016 --> 00:15:55.386 A:middle
I noticed that boys
would build for the sake

00:15:55.386 --> 00:15:56.856 A:middle
of building all day long.

00:15:56.986 --> 00:15:59.686 A:middle
They would build it
up and smash it down

00:15:59.906 --> 00:16:00.886 A:middle
and do it again and again.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:15:59.906 --> 00:16:00.886 A:middle
and do it again and again.

00:16:01.596 --> 00:16:04.616 A:middle
I noticed that the girls
really liked stories

00:16:04.616 --> 00:16:06.856 A:middle
and characters, they
liked narrative.

00:16:06.926 --> 00:16:09.216 A:middle
They didn't just want to
build, but they'd want

00:16:09.386 --> 00:16:11.326 A:middle
to build something
for a purpose, like,

00:16:11.326 --> 00:16:14.306 A:middle
why are we building it and who
is it for, and who is it going

00:16:14.366 --> 00:16:17.426 A:middle
to help, and where is it, and
what's the story behind it?

00:16:18.316 --> 00:16:23.106 A:middle
And so all of this research
kind of led me to an "aha" way

00:16:23.106 --> 00:16:24.596 A:middle
to engage girls in building.

00:16:25.726 --> 00:16:28.046 A:middle
It was a really simple
idea, but I thought,

00:16:28.046 --> 00:16:30.816 A:middle
what if I combined
building with a story?

00:16:31.686 --> 00:16:35.606 A:middle
I came up with this
character that I invented,

00:16:35.606 --> 00:16:38.826 A:middle
named GoldieBlox, and she
would be the girl builder,

00:16:38.826 --> 00:16:39.826 A:middle
a girl engineer.

00:16:40.266 --> 00:16:42.836 A:middle
And she'd go on adventures
and have to solve problems

00:16:42.836 --> 00:16:44.306 A:middle
by building contraptions.

00:16:44.616 --> 00:16:48.496 A:middle
And I thought if girls thought
she was cool and they wanted

00:16:48.496 --> 00:16:50.426 A:middle
to be like her and
do what she does,

00:16:50.426 --> 00:16:52.916 A:middle
then maybe that would
get them to build, too,

00:16:53.226 --> 00:16:54.696 A:middle
and maybe the little machines

00:16:54.696 --> 00:16:57.596 A:middle
that they build can teach
them engineering principles

00:16:57.596 --> 00:16:59.666 A:middle
and help solve problems,
give that context

00:16:59.996 --> 00:17:01.236 A:middle
that girls were looking for.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:16:59.996 --> 00:17:01.236 A:middle
that girls were looking for.

00:17:01.776 --> 00:17:05.876 A:middle
So this was my genius idea,
this engineering toy for girls.

00:17:06.715 --> 00:17:09.685 A:middle
And I became so obsessed
with it,

00:17:09.685 --> 00:17:14.496 A:middle
it led me to my next audacious
goal: build a startup.

00:17:15.846 --> 00:17:19.715 A:middle
So at the time when I came
up with this engineering toy

00:17:19.715 --> 00:17:21.715 A:middle
for girls, I was working

00:17:21.715 --> 00:17:25.776 A:middle
at a pretty cushy nine-to-five
job, steady paycheck.

00:17:26.396 --> 00:17:28.286 A:middle
And, in fact, ever
since I was old enough

00:17:28.356 --> 00:17:31.126 A:middle
to work I always had
a job, so the thought

00:17:31.126 --> 00:17:33.726 A:middle
of actually leaving it and
starting out on my own,

00:17:33.726 --> 00:17:35.336 A:middle
it was pretty terrifying.

00:17:36.006 --> 00:17:38.666 A:middle
But it got to the point
where I was so obsessed

00:17:38.836 --> 00:17:40.746 A:middle
with GoldieBlox it was
all I could think about,

00:17:40.746 --> 00:17:43.916 A:middle
all I could talk about,
it got to the point

00:17:43.916 --> 00:17:44.996 A:middle
where it didn't feel
like a choice,

00:17:44.996 --> 00:17:48.046 A:middle
it felt like it was
just what I had to do.

00:17:48.696 --> 00:17:52.736 A:middle
So I decided to give myself one
year, I'm going to go for it.

00:17:52.876 --> 00:17:56.166 A:middle
I have enough money in my bank
account that if by the end

00:17:56.166 --> 00:18:00.136 A:middle
of one year this doesn't work
out, then I can always just go


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:17:56.166 --> 00:18:00.136 A:middle
of one year this doesn't work
out, then I can always just go

00:18:00.136 --> 00:18:01.346 A:middle
and get another job, right?

